A person just starting out leading a raid is going to have a lot to learn about this and it will take lots of patience.<br>
<br>
Yes, Vox and Naggy are where raid leaders start learning usually,  I cant think of too many 40-50 people raids before that.<br>
<br>
If the raid leader ignored you on purpose then ya, get upset/quit/etc.<br>
<br>
How likely is this? very slight...if he/she didnt want you there then you'd wouldnt have been invited.<br>
<br>
Obviously he didnt see you say looking for a group.  A common mistake that just happens.<br>
<br>
I lead these kind of raids 3-4+ times a week, very experienced at it and I miss people all the time.  Although lately the 'grouping' job is delegated to someone else ( try it ).<br>
<br>
My suggestion is to have some patience.<br>
<br>
Yes, say lfg in the raid channel a few times at first.<br>
<br>
If that doesnt get his attention ( easily missed as sometimes there are many channels to moniter ( raid, group, healer, leader, etc. ) then send him/her a few tells.<br>
<br>
If that doesnt work, ask someone else helping the raid who's in charge a bit... puller, etc.<br>
<br>
If that doesnt work, spam the hell out of the channel till he see's it.<br>
<br>
More then likely you see him/her say, &quot;crap, sorry I missed ya&quot;<br>
<br>
If that still doesnt work then ya, you need to leave because you are being ignored at this point on purpose.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Most of the times I've seen this happen is because people ignore the raid leader saying &quot;join /raidchannel everyone&quot; and since a lot of the times the groups are made out of the list of folks in that channel then you'll be missed.<br>
<br>
But that is a problem with the raider ignoring the commands of the raidleader and the raiders fault.  Most of the times, this is who to blame.<br>
<br>
<br>
But hell, groups usually arent made at first at vox/naggy raids anyways... just make up a group to clear the path to where you stage for the raid.<br>
<br>
Pal<br>
